@NODE "IntroText" "INTRODUCTION"

INTRODUCTION

InterBase has been designed as simple and intuitive database system for 
the average user with little or no technical experience. When we were 
designing InterBase, user-friendliness, simplicity and flexibility were 
considered to be the most important factors.

By concentrating on the functions necessary for inputting, manipulating 
and presenting your data, we have ensured that InterBase is simple to use. 
However, these functions have been designed to be as flexible as possible 
so that they can be combined to perform far more complex operations.

InterBase gives you almost unlimited control over the way your data is 
presented and can easily be modified according to your specific needs. 
It also guarantees that your data is presented in a consistent manner 
regardless of whether it's output to the screen, a file or a printer. This 
vast flexibility also enables you to exchange data between InterBase and 
other programs.

InterBase uses the Amiga's graphic user interface (GUI, sometimes referred 
to as Intuition) to give you instant easy access to all of its features. 
If you've used any other packages which use the Intuition interface you 
will feel instantly at home using InterBase.

@ENDNODE


@NODE "APPENDIX A" "THE INTERBASE FILE REQUESTER"

The InterBase File Requester which is used to select file names for 
functions such as Open Environment and Open Table.

Close Window 
   The little square gadget in the top left hand corner, this closes 
   the window without taking any further action.

Drawer 
   Default: current directory 

   This is where you specify the disk and/or directory name containing 
   the file/s that you want to load or save. InterBase will accept 
   absolute path names such as 'Data:Address', or you can refer to 
   logical devices such as drives and assignments, eg, 'DF0:Address'. 
   The text gadget is not case sensitive, so it doesn't matter if you 
   use capital or lower case letters, or a mixture of both.

   If you don't want to type in a path name, or you are not exactly sure 
   of the correct path to give, you can use the mouse to enter one. 
   Having chosen the appropriate drive or device via one of the Volume 
   gadgets (see below), the contents of the selected drive will be shown 
   in the File Display List. This File Display List is arranged in 
   alphabetical order and each entry (line) has three pieces of 
   information associated with it. The first is the actual name of the 
   drawer or file. The second is used to tell you whether a name is a 
   file or a drawer. Drawers have the word 'Drawer' after their name, 
   whilst files have a number representing their size in bytes. The final 
   column shows the date when the drawer or file was created, or last 
   edited. Each time you save or re-save a file, the current system time 
   and date will be added to its file name. Of course, if your computer 
   doesn't have a battery backed clock, this time and date will be wrong 
   unless you set the clock each time you load the program.


File
   If you want to save a file using an existing file name, click on 
   the appropriate file name when it appears in the File Display List, 
   and it will be automatically inserted in the File text gadget. 
   Alternately, you can type in the name that you want to give the file. If
   you are saving a new file, you must enter a file name in this text 
   gadget.

Parent
   This gadget takes you back up a level within the current device.

Read Drawer
   When you've selected a particular drawer, either by clicking on its 
   name, clicking one of the gadgets or typing its name into the drawer 
   text gadget, InterBase will look at the contents of that drawer, and 
   list them in the File Display List. If you save a file and return to 
   the Open or Save requesters, the file that you saved will not be shown 
   in the File Display List because the drawer's contents have already 
   been read once. The Read Drawer gadget tells InterBase to re-read and 
   display the contents of the current drawer so that all files are shown.

Open/Save
   This button (found just below the Read Drawer gadget) is used to 
   perform the action associated with the function you have selected. 
   If you are opening an environment, table or layout it will read Open, 
   if you are saving it will read Save.

Volume Gadgets
   These gadgets represent any 'physical' storage devices you may have 
   connected such as a hard drive (DH0:), memory (RAM:) or a floppy drive 
   (DF0:, DF1:, etc.). By clicking on one of them the contents of this 
   device will be read and displayed in the File Display List.

Cancel
   Exits the File Requester without performing any actions, this gadget 
   has the same effect as clicking on the Close Window gadget described 
   above.

@endnode

@NODE "APPENDIX B" "DISK OPERATIONS"

InterBase offers an easy method of performing simple disk operations such 
as deleting and renaming files.

By selecting Project/Disk Operations a window similar to the File 
Requester is opened. All of the File Requester functions are repeated 
here plus several new ones as follows:

Open 
   Attempts to open the currently selected file as an Environment. This 
   is the same as using Project/Open Environment.

Save
   Attempts to save the current environment under the name currently 
   selected. This is the same as using Project/Save.

Make Drawer
   Prompts you to enter the name of a new drawer, which is then created 
   in the current directory (this directory is re-read and the File 
   Display List is updated).

Erase
   Prompts you to confirm your action then permanently deletes the 
   currently selected file.

Rename
   Prompts you to type in the new name of the currently selected file, 
   then renames it accordingly. Again the File Display List is re-read 
   to show your changes.

Close
   Exits the Disk Operations Window.

@endnode

@NODE "APPENDIX C" "STRUCTURE OF EXPRESSIONS"

InterBase's expressions come in many shapes and sizes and must follow 
the rules listed below.

All expressions must consist of a simple expression followed by zero or 
more relational-operators and simple expression combinations. ie.

Expression Relational-operator Expression

Here are some specific examples:

Cost - simple expression with no operators
Cost=0 - simple expression with one relational-operator (=) 
Cost*21
Cost+Tax
Cost+Tax<>98 OR Profit=>(Retail/100*60)

A relational operator is one of =,<>,<,>,<=,>=.

A simple expression consists of a sign (+ or -) and a term. Expressions 
without a sign are assumed to be positive (+).

A term can be a fieldname, a constant value or the result of a 
mathematical function.	
For example:

	fieldname 	+	fieldname
        fieldname 	- 	constant
	constant	or 	fieldname
	factor   	and	term
	factor 		/	term
	factor 		*	term

A factor is one of the following:

	constant
	fieldname
	function call
	(expression)
	not factor

A constant refers to any real number (a positive or negative number 
with or without decimal places)  or a string (any characters enclosed 
in quotation marks). The exponential numbering system may also be used.

A fieldname is either the name of a field in the current table or one 
defined in a relation. If you are referring to a field name in a relation 
you should use the following syntax: 
!relationid.fieldname

Relationid is the name of you gave to the relation.

A function call can be one of the following:

	today	which returns the current system date.
	now	which returns the current system time.
	pageno	which returns the current page number.

@endnode

@NODE "APPENDIX D" "FORMATS"

Formatting strings tell InterBase how to format certain types of data 
for display and are dependant upon the type of data being formatted.

NUMBER FORMATS

Number formatting is used to specify how many characters should be 
displayed to the left or right of a number's decimal point.

The formatting string always begins with the '%' percent character and 
those of you familiar with the 'C' programming language will instantly 
recognise these strings as those used by the 'printf' type functions.

The format of the string is as follows:-

% [-] [Length] [.] [Precision] Notation

Everything enclosed in square brackets ('[]') is optional and is defined 
as follows.

'-'
   Used to described a negative length (see 'length' below).

Length
   States the minimum number of characters to be printed. If the number 
   contains less characters than the specified length space characters 
   will be inserted BEFORE the number (thus right justifying the number 
   to the specified length). If the length begins with a zero then the 
   '0' (zero) character will be used instead of spaces. Finally, if length 
   is negative (preceded by a '-' (minus) sign) then the number will be 
   left justified, that is to say the padding will occur on the right hand 
   side of the number.

'.'
   Indicates that the precision function is to be used. 

Precision
   The value of precision defines the number of characters to print the 
   right of the decimal point (if any). Thus defining how 'precise' or 
   accurate the number will be. If the number has to be truncated 
   (because it's longer than the value of precision) the last number to 
   be displayed is rounded up if the next number is greater than five, 
   and down if it is less than or equal o five.

Notation: The single character value defines how the number is treated 
according to the value below.


'f' The number is printed as a floating point decimal. This means that 
zeros are placed after the decimal place to pad the number out to the 
required number of digits.

'e' The number is printed using exponential format using a lower case 'e'.

'E' The number is printed using exponential format using an uppercase 'E'.

'g' The number is printed using exponential format or common floating 
point which ever is the shorter and uses a lower case 'e' for the 
exponential format. This is the default number format.

'G' The number is printed using exponential format or common floating 
point which ever is the shorter and uses a uppercase 'E' for the 
exponential format.

See manual for examples


DATE FORMATS

Date formatting is used to specify whether dates should be displayed as 
numbers, words or a combination of both. It is also used to specify the 
order in which the day, month and year should be shown.

The formatting string is made up with a number of special characters 
which are replaced with the relevant parts of the date.

Character		Result
'd'			Tells InterBase to show the day of the month as a 
			number.

'dd'			The same as 'd' but the number is always two 
			characters long (a preceding zero is added where 
			necessary.

'ddd'			The day of the week is displayed abbreviated to 
			three characters (Mon, Tue, Wed, Thu, Fri, Sat 
			and Sun).

'dddd'			The entire day name is displayed.

'm'			The number of the month is displayed.

'mm'			The same as 'm' but the figure displayed always 
			contains two characters, again preceded by a zero 
			where necessary.

'mmm'			The month name is displayed as a three letter 
			abbreviation (Jan, Feb, Mar, Apr, May, Jun, Jul, 
			Aug, Sep, Oct, Nov and Dec).

'mmmm'			The entire month name is displayed.

'y' or 'yy'		Only the last two digits of the year are shown, ie 
			93 for 1993.

'yyy' or 'yyyy'		The entire year number is displayed, ie 1993.

'\x'			The character x is printed 'as-is' any special
			formatting is ignored.

Any other characters used in a date formatting string will be displayed 
exactly as you enter them. Therefore you can insert hyphens '-', 
backslashes '/' or any form of date punctuation.

See manual for examples

@endnode

@NODE "APPENDIX E" "TECHNICAL INFORMATION"

Although where possible we have tried to avoid any limitations in 
InterBase, there are a few you should be aware of.

FIELD TYPE LIMITATIONS

Dynamic Strings (DStrings)
   A DString may not be any longer than 9999 characters. Each DString 
   record requires ten bytes of disk space or RAM more than its length. 
   For example, a record which is 32 characters long will actually occupy 
   42 bytes of space.

Fixed Strings (FStrings)
   An FString's length is only limited by the amount of available RAM 
   or disk space. Each FString record requires an additional two bytes 
   of space more than the length of the field.

Numbers
   Numbers are represented internally as a 64 bit floating point number 
   in standard IEEE format. Each Number field uses nine bytes of 
   Disk/RAM space.

Dates
   Dates are represent internally as a 32 bit integer allowing a range 
   from January 1st 0001 to some time after the year 5,000,000. Each Date 
   field uses five bytes of Disk/RAM space.

LIMITATIONS ON NAMES

The names of table fields, layouts, relations and environments are 
limited to eight characters in length. The first character must be an 
alphabetic character (a-z or A-Z) the remainder may be letters or numbers.

A table's User ID and password is limited to ten characters in length and 
any characters may be used.

LIMITATIONS ON LAYOUTS

The combined height of the three (Header, Body and Footer) sub-layouts 
is limited to the height of the screen (non-interlaced), ie. 26 lines.

The width of a layout field is limited to the width of the screen 
(77 characters).

Initial values and expressions (in layouts fields) are limited to 30 
characters in length.

Expressions may not refer to the results of other expressions. Therefore 
if the field 'Tax' contains information calculated by the expression 
'tax=income/25' you may NOT have another field which uses an expression 
such as this: 'VAT=tax/25*17.5'.

Search and Update expressions are limited to 255 characters long.

INTERBASE FILES

The following list describes the different file types created and used by 
InterBase for tables, layouts, relations and environments.

Tables
  Every time you define a table InterBase automatically creates four 
  files. Each file has a name of the form 'tablename.XXX' where tablename 
  is the name defined by you when creating the table and XXX is one of:

   .TDF
      Table Definition File. Contains the structure of the table, 
      User ID, password etc. Information about the default layout file 
      and any relations which use this table as the source table.

   .DTA
      DaTA. This is where the data (contents) of the table stored.

   .PKT
      This file contains information on the construction of the .DTA 
      file such as where (within the .DTA file) the individual records 
      are stored.

   .LOT
      LayOuT. When you create a table, a default layout is assigned to it. 
      This default or any subsequent modifications will be stored with a 
      .LOT extension.

Relations

Relations are stored in a file with the name that was specified when the 
relation was created, followed by the characters .REL. Because each 
relation also has an associated table, a set of three (.TDF, .DTA and 
.PKT) table files are created (relations do not have a layout file). 
Therefore you should NOT give relations the same name as any existing tables.

Environments

Environment files have an extension of .MIL. As well as storing your 
preferences for the specified environment, a .MIL file also contains a 
list of the environment's tables and layouts.

THE FILEID UTILITY

If you rename a file and forget what type it is, you can use the FILEID 
utility to identify it. FILEID can be found on the InterBase master disk,
and it is accessed from CLI or SHELL in the following manner:

	FileID filename [filename...]

filename is the command's only argument, and naturally enough, it's the 
name of the unidentified file. You can request the identity of as many 
files as you require provided each filename is separated from the 
previous one by a space.

FileID will then identify each of the files. This identification 
consists of the word 'InterBase', the version number of the software 
used to create this file and a file-type description (see the file 
extensions section above).

@endnode

@NODE "APPENDIX F" "MENU SUMMARIES"

Here is a list of all of InterBase's menus items and brief summary of 
their function. Where applicable keyboard shortcuts and/or Icon Bar 
icons are mentioned.

MAIN MENU

   PROJECT MENU
      New Environment 
         The current environment (all tables, data and layouts) are 
         closed and removed from memory.

      Open Environment
         Allows you to select a new environment to load into memory. 
         Clicking on Open will remove the current environment and load the 
         new one.

      Save
         Saves the current environment using its current name (as displayed
         after the word Project in the Main Status bar).

      Save as
         Saves the current environment under the name specified by you in 
         the file requester.

      Disk Operations
         Opens the InterBase Disk Operations window and allows simple DOS 
         commands. See Appendices A and B for more information.

      Preferences
         Allows you to alter InterBase's default configuration parameters
         such as the default number format and the where to place 
         temporary files.

      About InterBase
         Gives information about this release of InterBase including 
         the version number and its authors.

      Quit InterBase
         After prompting for confirmation, closes all tables and layouts 
         and exits InterBase.

   EDIT MENU

      New Record
         Adds a new record to the end of the current table and places 
         the cursor in the first editable field ready for your input.

      Copy Record
         Prompts you to select an existing record which is then copied 
         to the end of the current table and readied for your input.

      Delete Record
         Prompts you to select a record which is then deleted.

      Cut
         Removes the contents of the current field and copies them to 
         the clipboard.

      Copy
         Copies the contents of the current field and store them in the 
         clipboard file.

      Paste
         Copy the contents of the clipboard file into the current field.

   TABLE MENU

      Define Table 
         Allows you to define a new table or modify an existing one 
         (see the manual: Beginners Guide - Creating a Table and the 
         Advanced Guide - Tables for more information).

      Open Table
         Loads a table from disk and places it in the current environment.

      Close Table
         Saves any changes made to the current table and removes it from 
         the current environment.

      Unlock Table
         Using the InterBase file requester to 'Unlock' a 'locked' table. 
         The most likely cause for a table being locked is that the power 
         was turned off (or the Amiga was reset) without first saving or 
         closing the table.

      Current Table
         Specifies which table in the current environment is to be the 
         active one.

      Set Default Layout
         Lets you specify which layout in the current environment is to 
         be the default. The default layout is then used to display the 
         contents of all new tables until you either alter the layout 
         for each table individually, or until you create a new default.

      Reset Selection
         Cancels the effect of all searches and sorts and resets the 
         selection so that all records in the current table are included.

   LAYOUT MENU

      Define Layout
         Allows you to modify or create a layout and enters the Layout 
         Editor. The Layout Editor has its own menu which is summarised 
         in the next section (see the Manual: Beginners Guide - Creating 
         a Database and the Advanced Guide - Layouts for more information).

      Open Layout
         Loads a layout from disk to the current environment.

      Close Layout
         Saves any changes made to the current layout and removes it 
         from the current environment.

      Current Layout 
         Lets you specify a layout to use for the current table. If you 
         choose a layout containing fields which are not available in the 
         current table, an error message will appear.

   VARIOUS MENU

      Define Relation
         Let's you define a relationship between two tables.

      Operations
         This sub-menu allows you to perform several 'set' operations 
         on one or two tables. See the Manual: Advanced Guide - Operations 
         for more information.

      Select
         Performs the select operation which copies a table, creating a 
         new one in the process.

      Union
         Performs the mathematical union operation which joins two 
         similar tables to create a new one.

      Intersection
         Performs the mathematical intersection operation which takes 
         matching entries from two similar tables to produce a new one.

      Difference
         Performs the mathematical difference operation which takes 
         non-matching entries from two similar tables to produce a new one.

      Join
         Joins two dissimilar tables using one or more 'key' fields. 
         This results in a new table containing all non-key fields and
         one field from each key pair.

      Freetext Search
         Performs a search on string type fields within the current 
         table. Until Table/Reset Selection is selected or another search 
         is performed, only table entries which match the search criteria 
         will be included in the current selection for display. See the 
         Manual: Beginners Guide - Searching and the Advanced Guide - Using
         Wildcards in Freetext Searches for more information.

      Expression Search
         Performs a search on any specified fields in the current table. 
         Until Table/Reset Selection is selected or another search is 
         performed, only entries for which the expression evaluates as 
         true will be included in the current selection for display. See 
         the Manual: Advanced Guide - Expression Searches for more 
         information.

      Sort
         Sorts the current selection into ascending or descending order 
         using up to four fields as the sort keys.

      Update
         Uses an expression to update fields in the current table (unless 
         they are update protected).

      Statistics
         Displays statistics about the tables in the current environment.

      Print
         Sends the contents of the current table using the current layout 
         to the printer. The printer must be correctly configured using 
         the standard  Amiga printer preferences programs found on the 
         InterBase Workbench disk.

      Write to file
         Writes the contents of the current table, using the current layout
         to a disk file.

      Import from ASCII File
         Imports ASCII data into the current table.

      Export to ASCII File
         Exports the current table's data as an ASCII file. This file 
         may then be load into another program such as a database or 
         text editor.

      Write Mail Merge Format
         Writes the contents of the current table to a file which can be 
         imported into InterWord using its Mail Merge function.

   SPECIAL MENU

      Interlace
         Toggles between standard and interlaced screen modes.

      Palette
         Lets you modify the colours used in InterBase.


LAYOUT EDITOR MENUS

When you are using the Layout editor, InterBase will frequently give 
you messages which will appear in the menu at the top of the screen. 
These messages will usually inform you exactly what action you are 
expected to take.

For more information about these commands see the Manual: Advanced 
Guide - The Layout Editor.


LAYOUT MENU

   Size of SubLayout
      Lets you modify the size of the three (Header, Body and Footer)
      sub-layouts.

   Copy Layout
      Allows you to select another layout from the current environment 
      and copy it to the layout editor, this process deletes the current 
      contents of the editor.

   Cancel Editing
      Leaves the layout editor without saving any changes to the layout.

   Quit Layout
      Saves any changes made to the layout and leaves the layout editor.

EDIT MENU

   New Field
      Creates a new layout field and prompts you to indicate where it 
      is to be positioned.

   Delete Field
      Prompts you to select a layout field then deletes it.

   Move Field
      Allows you to select a field and reposition it within the current 
      layout.

   Copy Field
      Allows you to select an existing field and duplicate it at a 
      position of your choice.


OPTIONS MENU

   Fixed Coordinates
      Toggles between pixel and character positioning.

   SubLayout Autosize
      Toggles between automatic and manual sizing of Sub-Layouts. If 
      automatic is selected any blank lines in the layout will be removed.

@endnode


@NODE "APPENDIX G" "ERROR MESSAGES"

This chapter gives detailed descriptions of the error messages that you 
might encounter whilst using InterBase. Every error is explained and a 
method of eliminating the problem is given.


