@NODE E-1 "Error 1"

1. "Can't Open File"

InterBase was not able to open a file. This error may occur at any time 
whilst trying to read or write any type of file (table, layout, 
environment etc.). There are two possible causes for this message:

Cause: You specified an incorrect file or path name.

Solution: Click on Cancel and modify the file/path name.

Cause: Incorrect disk inserted.

Solution: Insert the correct disk and click Repeat.
@endnode

@NODE E-2 "Error 2"

2. "Error reading"

An error was encountered whilst reading a file. This may be caused 
by a corrupted or defective diskette.

Cause: Defective media.

Solution: Try clicking on Repeat a few times.

Solution: Repair the disk using Disk Doctor (supplied on your Workbench 
disk) or DiskSalv (a superior program by Dave Haynie) which is available 
from all good public domain companies.
@endnode

@NODE E-3 "Error 3"

3. "Error writing"
An error occurred whilst writing a file. This may be caused by a 
corrupted or defective diskette.

Cause: Defective media.

Solution: Try clicking on Repeat a few times.

Solution: Repair the disk using Disk Doctor (supplied on your Workbench 
disk) or DiskSalv (a superior program by Dave Haynie) which is available 
from all good public domain companies.
@endnode

@NODE E-4 "Error 4"

4. "Can't close file"

InterBase couldn't close a file this could be due to an incorrect 
filename, incorrect disk inserted or defective media.

Cause: You specified an incorrect file or path name.

Solution: Click on Cancel and modify the file or path name.

Cause: Incorrect disk inserted.

Solution: Insert the correct disk and click Repeat.

Cause: Defective media.

Solution: Try clicking Repeat a few times.

Solution: Repair the disk using Disk Doctor (supplied on your Workbench 
disk) or DiskSalv (a superior program by Dave Haynie) which is available 
from all good public domain companies.
@endnode

@NODE E-5 "Error 5"

5. "InterBase needs free memory"

InterBase could not allocate enough memory for the specified function. 
Click Repeat after trying one (or more) of the solutions below.

Solution: Close any additional opened applications.

Solution: Close any open windows or drawers on your Workbench screen.

Solution: Close any unused tables and layouts.

@endnode

@NODE E-6 "Error 6"

6. "Unknown or wrong filetype"

A file was not of the type specified. ie. A file with an extension of 
.LOT was not a layout file. See Appendix G - Technical Information for a 
description of file types.

Cause: A file name has been changed.

Solution: Use the FileID program to find the file type and change the name 
accordingly. See Appendix G - Technical Information for further details 
about the FileID utility.

Cause: Corrupt file or defective storage media.

Solution: Try clicking Repeat a few times.

Solution: Repair the disk using Disk Doctor (supplied on your Workbench 
disk) or DiskSalv (a superior program by Dave Haynie) which is available 
from all good public domain companies.
@endnode

@NODE E-7 "Error 7"

7."Table is locked"

An attempt to open a 'locked' table was made.

Cause: On a multi-user system another user may currently be using the 
table .

Solution: Wait for the person who is currently using the table, to close 
it.

Cause: The table was not closed due to a system error (a power failure 
for example).

Solution: Unlock the table using the Table/Unlock Table function.

@endnode

@NODE E-8 "Error 8"

8."Error in expression"

An expression did not use the correct syntax.

Solution: See Appendix E - Definition of Expressions.

@endnode

@NODE E-9 "Error 9"

9."Illegal Identifier"
The table, layout, relation or environment name does not conform to 
the rules laid out in Appendix G - Technical Information.

Solution: Read the relevant section and adjust the name accordingly.

@endnode

@NODE E-10 "Error 10"

10. "Illegal drawer"

The drawer name specified in the File Requester could not be read.

Solution: Check the entered drawer name against the existing drawer 
name to ensure that you have spelt it correctly.

@endnode

@NODE E-11 "Error 11"

11. "None or all key fields must be defined"

A relation was defined but an incorrect number of key-fields were defined.

Solution: Define the required number of key-fields.

@endnode

@NODE E-12 "Error 12"

12. "Source-table of relation not current table"
After selecting a current layout or quitting from editing a layout, 
a relation is referred to whose source table is not current.

Solution: Remove the incorrect references from the layout.

Solution: Select the relation's source table as the current table.

@endnode

@NODE E-13 "Error 13"

13. "Relation referenced but not all key-fields included in layout"

A layout refers to relation but does not contain all the key-fields of 
the relationship.

Solution: Add the rest of the key-fields to the layout.

Solution: Remove all references to the relation from the layout.

@endnode

@NODE E-14 "Error 14"

14. "Field already exists"

You tried to define a field name which is the same as one which already 
exists in the current table.

Solution: Select a new name for your field.

@endnode

@NODE E-15 "Error 15"

15. "Can't make drawer"

InterBase couldn't create the specified drawer.

Solution: Check the specified path name to see if a file or drawer 
already exists with the same name.

Solution: Check that the path name specified for the new drawer 
actually exists.

@endnode

@NODE E-16 "Error 16"

16. "No fields defined"

You have attempted to define a table with no fields.

Solution: Cancel the table definition.

Solution: Add at least one field to the table.

@endnode

@NODE E-17 "Error 17"

17."Can't close a default layout"

You tried to close the default layout belonging to one of the tables 
in the current environment.

Solution: Close the table in question.

Solution: Choose another default layout for the table.

@endnode

@NODE E-18 "Error 18"

18. "At least one field must be selected"

An attempt was made to perform the Join operation without selecting 
any key-fields.

Solution: Select at least one key-field.

@endnode

@NODE E-19 "Error 19"

19. "Field type mismatch"

While 'weak-type checking' for a Join operation the selected key-fields 
in the two argument tables were found to be incompatible. For example, 
one was a DString and the other was a number.

Solution: Select compatible key-fields.

@endnode

@NODE E-20 "Error 20"

20. "Field count mismatch"

In a Join operation the same number of fields were not selected from 
the two argument tables.

Solution: Make your selections again ensuring that you select the same 
number of fields from each table.

@endnode

@NODE E-21 "Error 21"

21. "No current table"

You tried to perform a function on a table when no current table was 
available.

Solution: Select or Open a table.

@endnode

@NODE E-22 "Error 22"

22. "Destination table same as Source table"

You attempted to create a relation using the same table as the 
Destination and Source.

Solution: Select two different tables.

@endnode

@NODE E-23 "Error 23"

23. "Illegal link"
An reference was made in a layout field to a relation or field which 
doesn't exist.

Solution: Check the field name used.

@endnode

@NODE E-24 "Error 24"

24. "Relation already exists"

A relation was created with the same name as one which already exists 
in the current environment.

Solution: Choose a new name for the relation.

@endnode

@NODE E-25 "Error 25"

25. "The field must be unique"

An attempt was made to add or modify the contents of a field which has 
the Unique attribute flag set, to that of an existing entry. 

Solution: Modify the entry so that it is different from all others in 
the same field.

@endnode

@NODE E-26 "Error 26"

26. "The field is obligatory"

An Obligatory field has been left empty.

Solution: Enter data into the field.

@endnode

@NODE E-27 "Error 27"

27. "Drawer/file already exists"

In the Disk Operations window an attempt was made to create a drawer 
or file which already exists.

Solution: Modify the name of the drawer or file you are attempting to create.

@endnode

@NODE E-28 "Error 28"

28. "Table/layout already in environment"

An attempt was made to open a table or layout which already exists 
in the current environment.

Solution: Select the table or layout using the Current Table or Current
Layout menu items.

@endnode

@NODE E-29 "Error 29"

29. "Invalid number"

You tried to enter a non-numeric value in a number field.

Solution: Enter the number correctly. Remember the digits 0-9, the 
letter 'E' and a decimal point (.) are  the ONLY characters allowed 
in a number field.

@endnode

@NODE E-30 "Error 30"

30. "Incorrect password"

Upon opening a password protected table an incorrect password was entered.

Solution: If you are sure you know the correct password, try entering it 
again in case you made a typing error.

Solution: Refer to the person who protected the table for the correct 
password.

Cause: You have forgotten or lost a password that you defined.

Solution: You will have to send a copy of your database to 
InterActivision for de-protection. Write to us for further details.

@endnode

@NODE E-31 "Error 31"

31. "Length must be at least 1"

A length of less than one was  specified for a layout field.

Solution: Specify a length or one or more.

@endnode

@NODE E-32 "Error 32"

32. "Incorrect expression type"

An incorrect expression was entered for the Expression Search or 
Update function.

Cause: The expression may have to be of the number type.

Solution: Correct the expression.

Cause: The expression is not of a type appropriate for the selected field.

Solution: Select another field. See Appendix E - Definition of Expressions.

@endnode

@NODE E-33 "Error 33"

33. "Reference to unknown field"

A field name which doesn't appear in the current table was referred to 
in a layout field.

Solution: Check the field names of the current table via Table/Define 
Table and correct the name accordingly.

@endnode

@NODE E-34 "Error 34"

34. "Table is a relation"

An attempt was made to open a table file which is actually a relation 
file.

Solution: Relation files CANNOT be opened on their own.

@endnode

@NODE E-35 "Error 35"

35. "Field name collision"

Fields from each of the argument tables in a Join operation have the same 
name.

Solution: Make the offending fields key-fields.

@endnode

@NODE E-36 "Error 36"

36. "Not IFF-picture format"

An attempt was made to display a file which was not in the IFF/ILBM 
format.

Solution: Non IFF pictures cannot be loaded under any circumstances, 
therefore your only option is to convert the required image into IFF 
using a package such as ASDG's Art Department Professional or Progressive 
Peripherals' Pixmate.

@endnode

@NODE E-37 "Error 37"

37. "Can't display IFF-picture"

An IFF file cannot be displayed because it uses a screen format not 
supported by your Amiga.

Solution: Convert the picture to a more acceptable format. ie, low 
resolution 32 colour.

@endnode

@NODE E-38 "Error 38"

38. Not used.

@endnode

@NODE E-39 "Error 39"

39. "Can't delete file:"

The named file cannot be deleted.

Cause: File is protected from deletion.

Solution: Modify the file protection bits using the AmigaDOS PROTECT 
command or the equivalent operation of a directory utility such as 
SID or Opus Directory.

@endnode

@NODE E-40 "Error 40"

40. "Can't create drawer:"

The named drawer cannot be created, possibly because a file or drawer 
of the same name already exists.

Solution: Try a different drawer name.

@endnode

@NODE E-41 "Error 41"

41. "Can't rename file:"

The named file cannot be renamed, possibly because a file or drawer with 
the new name already exists.

Solution: Use a different file name.

@endnode

@NODE "APPENDIX H" "GLOSSARY"

Argument Tables
   The source tables to InterBase's Operations.

Attribute
   See Field Attribute.

Cancel Area
   The blank area to the right of the Icon Bar which when clicked upon 
   cancels the current mode of operation.

Condition
   Part an expression, a condition is a test applied to the specified 
   fields, ie. County = "Essex".

Copy
   Copy the selected data TO the clipboard.

Cut
   Cut (Copy then delete) the selected data TO the clipboard.

Database
   A collection of data usually stored in a logical order for easy 
   reference, ie. an address book.

Data Window
   InterBase's main window where entries in your database are displayed.

Date
   A field type for storing dates. Stored internally as numbers, 
   dates can have most mathematical operations performed on them 
   (addition, subtraction, etc.)

Default Layout
   The layout which is initially used when a table is selected, each 
   table must have a default layout.

Depth Gadget
   The small square gadget in the top right hand corner of most screens 
   and windows, which allows the user to send the screen to the back of 
   all other screens.

Define Table Window
   A List window where you can select an existing table or type the 
   name of a new one.

Dynamic String
   A field type which can contain any type of textual data (words, 
   numbers, dates, punctuation, etc.). It automatically modifies its size 
   as required.

DString
   See Dynamic String.

Edit Protected
   Fields with this flag set cannot be edited by the user.

Environment
   A collection of tables, layouts and relations.

Expression
   A function which is applied to one or more fields to test for equality, 
   ie. Name = "Chris" or Price > 1000.

Expression Searches
   Using an expression search InterBase will create a temporary table 
   containing all entries which conform to the expression.

Field
   A sub-division of a table which is capable of holding data pertaining 
   to a single subject, ie, names, addresses, reference numbers, etc.

Field Attributes
   Special flags which are used to tell InterBase that entries in a field 
   must be treated in a particular way, ie, unique, obligatory, edit 
   protected, etc.

Field Priorities
   The order in which the fields are used to match the sort criteria.

File Requester
   A window displaying a list of files in the current directory from which 
   movement around the disk structure is allowed and files may be selected.

Fixed String
   A field type which can contain any type of textual data (words, numbers, 
   dates, punctuation, etc.) and which has fixed length regardless of the 
   size of any data it may contain.

FString
   See Fixed String.

Graphical User Interface
   A method of interacting with your computer by using icons 
   and pointers rather than typed commands.

GUI
   See Graphical User Interface.

InterBase Request
   A requester which prompts the user for confirmation of an option or 
   displays warning or error information.

Kickstart
   The collective name given to the Amiga's Operating System, which is 
   stored on a ROM chip inside your Amiga.

Icon Bar
   The row of icons just below the Main Status Bar which contain shortcuts 
   to the program's more commonly used functions.

Intuition
   The name given to the Amiga's Graphical User Interface (GUI).

Layout
   InterBase's method of displaying data.

Layout Editor
   The tool from where layouts are created and modified.

Layout Field
   A special field used in the Layout Editor to define how table 
   information is to be presented.

Main Status Bar
   The bar at the very top of the InterBase screen which is used to 
   display details about the current environment.

Number
   A field type which can contain a real (decimal) number in the range 
   00000+303 more zeros to +100000+303 more zeros.

Obligatory
   Fields with this flag set, force the user to enter some data, they 
   cannot be left blank.

Paste
   Copy the contents of the clipboard to the selected position.

Print Attributes
   Different styles used to highlight text in some way. ie. bold, 
   underline, etc.

Record
   The data contained in collection of related fields. For example a name, 
   address and phone number may comprise a single record in an address 
   table.

Relation
   A method of linking two tables together so that the information from 
   one may be accessed and viewed whilst using the other. This 'sharing' 
   of information means that identical information doesn't need to be 
   duplicated in two similar tables.

Relation Key Fields
   A list of fields which will be used in a relationship to define which 
   records from the related table are to be used.

Relational Operator
   Used to join two or more conditions a relational operator defines 
   the relationship between the conditions. For example,
   County = "Essex" OR County = "Kent" would be true if the 
   field County contained EITHER "Essex" or "Kent".

Relop
   See Relational Operator

Result Table
   The table used to store the results of InterBase's Operations.

Scroll Bar
   A gadget which can be dragged, usually to scroll through the contents 
   of a list or window.

Searching
   The process of selecting records from a table which match the textual 
   or other criteria specified by the user.

Sort Criteria
   Used to define which fields are used to sort the database.

String Gadget
   A standard Amiga gadget used to enter textual information.

Sub-layouts
   Three elements (Header, Body and Footer) which together comprise a 
   layout.

Table
   Also know as a database, a table contains information divided into 
   one or more related headings known as fields.

Unique
   Fields with this flag set must contain data which is different to that 
   of the same field of every other record in the current table.

Updating
   The process of replacing data in fields by evaluating an expression and 
   placing the result in the specified fields.

Update Protected
   Fields with this flag set will not be modified by InterBase's Update 
   function.

Weak Type Check
   A check to see if the field types in two tables are similar enough to 
   allow some form of comparison between them.

Wildcards
   Special characters which can be used to represent any individual 
   characters or sequences of characters, similar in concept to the joker 
   in a pack of cards.

Workbench
   A Program supplied with the Amiga (and InterBase) which allows you to 
   manipulate files and objects.

@endnode

